.SH NAME
\f[B]zelta\f[R] \- perform safe, recursive ZFS operations locally and
remotely
.SH SYNOPSIS
.IP
.EX
    zelta \-V | \-\-version
    zelta SUBCOMMAND [OPTIONS] [ARGUMENTS]
.EE
.SH DESCRIPTION
\f[B]zelta\f[R] provides tools for ZFS replication, backup verification,
dataset recovery, and policy\-based automation.
All operations work recursively on dataset trees and support both local
and remote execution via \f[B]ssh(1)\f[R].
.PP
Remote dataset endpoints follow \f[B]scp(1)\f[R] conventions:
[user\(at]host:[dataset].
Operations can be performed without installing \f[B]zelta\f[R] on remote
systems\(emonly standard ZFS utilities and SSH access are required.
.PP
Examples:
.IP
.EX
Local:  zpool/dataset\(atsnapshot
Remote: user\(atexample.com:zpool/dataset\(atsnapshot
.EE
.PP
See \f[B]zfs(8)\f[R] for dataset naming conventions.
.SH SUBCOMMANDS
For detailed usage of each subcommand, see the respective manual page.
.PP
\f[B]zelta help \f[R]
.TP
\f[B]zelta \-?\f[R]
Display help message.
.PP
\f[B]zelta \-V, \(enversion\f[R]
.TP
\f[B]zelta version\f[R]
Display version information.
.SS Comparison
.TP
\f[B]zelta match\f[R] \f[I]source\f[R] \f[I]target\f[R]
Compare two dataset trees and report matching snapshots or
discrepancies.
See \f[B]zelta\-match(8)\f[R].
.SS Replication
.TP
\f[B]zelta backup\f[R] \f[I]source\f[R] \f[I]target\f[R]
Replicate a dataset tree.
Creates snapshots if needed, detects optimal send options, and
replicates intermediate datasets.
See \f[B]zelta\-backup(8)\f[R].
.TP
\f[B]zelta sync\f[R] \f[I]source\f[R] \f[I]target\f[R]
Replicate only the most recent snapshot between dataset trees.
See \f[B]zelta\-sync(8)\f[R].
.SS Recovery
.TP
\f[B]zelta revert\f[R] \f[I]dataset\f[R]
Rewind a dataset to a previous snapshot by renaming and cloning.
Preserves current state.
See \f[B]zelta\-revert(8)\f[R].
.TP
\f[B]zelta rotate\f[R] \f[I]source\f[R] \f[I]target\f[R]
Preserve divergent dataset versions through rename and clone operations.
See \f[B]zelta\-rotate(8)\f[R].
.TP
\f[B]zelta clone\f[R] \f[I]dataset\f[R] \f[I]target\f[R]
Create a writable clone of a dataset tree.
See \f[B]zelta\-clone(8)\f[R].
.SS Automation
.TP
\f[B]zelta policy\f[R] [\f[I]options\f[R]]
Execute replication operations based on configuration file definitions.
See \f[B]zelta\-policy(8)\f[R].
.SH OPTIONS AND ENVIRONMENT
Configuration follows a hierarchy from lowest to highest precedence:
.IP
.EX
1. Built\-in defaults
2. \(ga/usr/local/etc/zelta/zelta.env\(ga
3. Policy configuration (\(gazelta.conf\(ga)
4. Environment variables
5. Command\-line arguments
.EE
.PP
See \f[B]zelta\-options(8)\f[R] for details.
.SH FILES
.TP
\f[B]/usr/local/etc/zelta/zelta.conf\f[R]
Default policy configuration file.
.TP
\f[B]/usr/local/etc/zelta/zelta.env\f[R]
Global default setting overrides.
.SH EXAMPLES
Replicate a dataset to a remote host:
.IP
.EX
zelta backup sink/data/project user\(atbackup.example.com:tank/backups/project
.EE
.PP
Compare local and remote dataset trees:
.IP
.EX
zelta match sink/data remote:tank/backups
.EE
.PP
Revert a dataset to its previous snapshot:
.IP
.EX
zelta revert sink/data/project
.EE
.PP
Update a target that has diverged:
.IP
.EX
zelta rotate sink/data/project user\(atbackup.example.com:tank/backups/project
.EE
.PP
Back up everything defined in policy settings.
.IP
.EX
zelta policy
.EE
